# Readers Hub

A Single Page Application (SPA) for discovering, saving, and exploring books using the Open Library API.
Readers Hub uses the Open Library API to dynamically fetch book data in real time. Instead of storing books locally, the application retrieves information directly from the API whenever a user performs a search or interacts with the app.

It allows the users to search the book and also allows the users to save the book that will be added to the fevorite section and also to view the details of the book that includes the title ,author name of the book and the cover at the read section

## Overview

Readers Hub is a frontend web application that allows users to explore and interact with books using the Open Library API.

It provides a smooth, Netflix-inspired browsing experience where users can:

- Search for books in real time
- View detailed book information at the read section
- Save favorite books
- Explore books in a Netflix-style layout
- Listen to book titles using text-to-speech
- ***

## Purpose

The purpose of Hub is to create a simple, engaging, and interactive platform for discovering books in a modern digital experience.

It is designed to:

Make book discovery fast and intuitive through realtime search help users build and manage a personal list of fevorite books provide easy access to detailed book information in one place and improve accesssibility by allowing users to listen to book titles using text to speech .It delivers a visually appealing browsing experience

The project focuses on strenghtening a core frontend development skills such as API integration,DOM manipulation and dynamic UI rendering using vanilla javaScript.

## Features

### Home section

The Home section is the main entry point of the Readers Hub application and is designed to provide users with an engaging and intuitive book discovery experience.

It serves as a dynamic dashboard where users can immediately start exploring books without any navigation complexity by using the form and the search button

The Home section enables users to:

Search for books instantly using keywords, titles, or authors
Receive live search results powered by the Open Library API
View updated results dynamically as they type, without page reloads

Books are displayed in a visually appealing horizontal scrolling layout, inspired by Netflix:

Rows of book cards are organized for easy browsing
Each card displays the book cover, title, and author

### Favorites Section

- Save books to localStorage
  When a user clicks the “save” button on a book the book fetched:

The book’s key details (title, author, cover image, and ID) are stored in the browser’s localStorage
This ensures the data is saved locally on the user’s device without requiring a backend database
Data is stored in JSON format for easy retrieval and manipulation

- View your personal library
  All saved books are displayed in a dedicated Favorites section, where users can:

see their saved collection

This section acts as a personal digital bookshelf.

- Persistent across sessions
  Because the data is stored in localStorage:

Favorites remain available even after refreshing the page
Data persists after closing and reopening the browser
No login or authentication is required

### Read Section (SPA View)

- Displays selected book details after fetching the book
- Includes title, author, and cover

### Text-to-Speech

- Listen to book titles

### Responsive Design

- Works across different screen sizes

---

## How It Works (SPA Architecture)

This project follows a Single Page Application approach:

- No page reloads
- Sections are toggled using JavaScript
- Views include:
  - Home
  - Favorites
  - Read

